@title "In the discipline of kinesics, methods of microanalysis of sound films of human communication have revealed that key elements of interaction exist in the gestures, postures, and configurations of movement accompanying speech (1-3). These methods, applied to interaction between neonate and caretaker, have revealed a synchronization of infant movement organization with the articulatory segments of adult speech as early as the first day of life."
